# [PROJECT NAME] — One-Shot Prompt

> A single, self-contained prompt that produces a complete deliverable in one
> pass (vibe coding). Good specs are specific about chart types, libraries,
> theme, and constraints — then let the AI make the hundreds of small decisions.

## The Spec

```
[Write the actual prompt here as a tight paragraph. Include:
 - What to build (the artifact)
 - Specific components / features (be concrete, e.g. "line chart, bar chart, donut chart")
 - Library choice (e.g. "use Chart.js from CDN") — naming it unlocks expert output
 - Theme / style direction (e.g. "dark theme, responsive grid")
 - Data direction (e.g. "generate realistic mock data")
 - Hard constraints (e.g. "single HTML file, no build step")]
```

## What Good Output Looks Like

- [Concrete element 1 the result should contain]
- [Concrete element 2]
- [Code-quality expectation, e.g. "single file, embedded CSS/JS, clean structure"]

## Iteration Ideas

Follow-up prompts to refine the first pass:

1. [e.g., "Add a date range picker for any 30-day window."]
2. [e.g., "Simulate live updates every 2 seconds."]
3. [e.g., "Add an Export as CSV button."]

## Why This Spec Works

- **Specific components**: no ambiguity about what to render.
- **Named library**: the agent applies expert knowledge instead of guessing.
- **Clear constraints**: architecture is decided, so effort goes into quality.
- **Right scope**: complete but bounded — one deliverable, one pass.
